 lsof` Cheat Sheet...

| Command | Purpose | Example |
|--------|--------|---------|
| `lsof` | List **all open files** on the system | `lsof` |
| `lsof /path/to/testfile.txt` | Check **if a file is open** | `lsof /Users/user/Desktop/testfile.txt` |
| `lsof +D /path/to/directory` | List **all files in a directory** being used | `lsof +D /Users/user/Desktop/` |
| `lsof -p PID` | List **all files used by a process** | `lsof -p 12345` |
| `lsof -i :port` | List **processes using a network port** | `lsof -i :80` |
| `lsof -u USER` | List **files used by a user** | `lsof -u user` |
| `lsof -c COMMAND` | List **files used by a command** | `lsof -c Terminal` |
| `lsof -d FD` | List **files with a specific file descriptor** | `lsof -d 3r` |
| `lsof -t /path/to/testfile.txt` | **Return only the PID** | `lsof -t /Users/user/Desktop/testfile.txt` |
| `lsof -c COMMAND -d FD` | Combine filters | `lsof -c Terminal -d 3r` |

---

### ЁЯФН How to Read the Output

When you run `lsof`, you get a table like this:

```
COMMAND     PID   USER   FD   TYPE DEVICE   SIZE/OFF   NODE NAME
Terminal   12345 user    3r   REG  1234567890  1024  1234567890 /Users/user/Desktop/testfile.txt
```

| Column | Meaning |
|--------|--------|
| `COMMAND` | Process name (e.g., `Terminal`) |
| `PID` | Process ID |
| `USER` | User who owns the process |
| `FD` | File descriptor (e.g., `3r` = read-only, `3w` = write) |
| `TYPE` | File type (`REG` = regular file, `DIR` = directory, `VNODE` = virtual file) |
| `DEVICE` | Device ID |
| `SIZE/OFF` | Size or offset in bytes |
| `NODE` | Inode number |
| `NAME` | Full path to the file |

